The paper deals with the problem of secure distributed matrix multiplication, which involves communication efficiency and security constraints. This suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), Computational Complexity (cs.CC), or Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. However, given the focus on secure communication and coding, cs.IT and cs.DC seem the most likely categories. The use of private information retrieval (PIR) also suggests a connection to cs.DS and cs.CC. Finally, the mention of cross-subspace alignment and transformation arguments could indicate a link to cs.SI.
